{{Infobox criminal | name = Dadullah | image = Mullah Dadullah TTP.jpg | image_size = 200px | caption = Mullah Dadullah | birth_name = Jamal Said | birth_date = c. 1965 | death_date = 24 August 2012 (46-47) | death_place = [[Shaigal Aw Shiltan District]], [[Afghanistan]] |cause = [[NATO]] airstrike | occupation = | religion = [[Islam]] | nationality = Pakistani }}
:''Not to be confused with the Afghan Taliban leader Mullah [[Dadullah]].'' '''Jamal Said''' (c. 1965 - 24 August 2012)<ref name="et20120826"/> better known by the ''[[Pseudonym|nom de guerre]]'' '''[[Mullah]] Dadullah'''<ref name=nyt25>{{cite news|last=Walsh|first=Declan|title=NATO Says Pakistani Militant Commander Killed in Afghanistan|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2012/08/26/world/asia/nato-says-it-killed-a-pakistani-militant-in-afghanistan.html|accessdate=25 August 2012|newspaper=The New York Times|date=25 August 2012|location=Islamabad}}</ref> and also '''Maulana Mohammad Jamal''',<ref name=lwarj/> was a senior member of the [[Tehrik-i-Taliban Pakistan|Pakistani Taliban]]. He was self-proclaimed Taliban leader in [[Pakistan]]'s northern [[Bajaur Agency]].<ref name=tguarap>{{cite news|title=Senior Taliban leader among those killed in Afghanistan air strike|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2012/aug/25/taliban-leader-kill-afghanistan-air-strike|accessdate=25 August 2012|newspaper=The Guardian|date=25 August 2012|agency=AP}}</ref> He was killed in a [[NATO]] airstrike in the [[Shaigal Aw Shiltan District|Shigal wa Sheltan District]] of [[Afghanistan]]'s neighbouring [[Kunar Province]] on 24 August 2012.<ref name=lwarj/><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.rferl.org/content/afghan-air-strike-kills-senior-pakistani-taliban-leader/24687557.html|title=Afghan Air Strike Kills Senior Pakistani Taliban Leader|work=Radio Free Europe|date=25 August 2012|accessdate=25 August 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.isaf.nato.int/article/isaf-releases/isaf-joint-command-morning-operational-update-aug.-23-2.html |title=ISAF Joint Command morning operational update |work=ISAF Joint Command |date=25 August 2012 |accessdate=25 August 2012 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120827044143/http://www.isaf.nato.int/article/isaf-releases/isaf-joint-command-morning-operational-update-aug.-23-2.html |archivedate=27 August 2012 |df= }}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/world/asia/taliban-leader-mullah-dadullah-dies-in-afghanistan-airstrike-8080964.html|title=Taliban leader Mullah Dadullah dies in Afghanistan airstrike|newspaper=The Independent|date=25 August 2012|accessdate=25 August 2012}}</ref> His deputy and ten Taliban fighters were also killed in the strike.<ref name=lwarj>{{cite journal|last=Roggio|first=Bill|title=Bajaur Taliban leader, deputy killed in airstrike in eastern Afghanistan|journal=Long War Journal|date=25 August 2012|url=http://www.longwarjournal.org/archives/2012/08/bajaur_taliban_leade.php|accessdate=27 August 2012}}</ref>
Dadullah was a former prayer leader and then became a Taliban commander.<ref name=nyt25/> It was reported by [[Associated Press|AP]] that Dadullah became leader of the group after Bajur's former Pakistani Taliban leader, [[Faqir Mohammed|Maulvi Faqir Mohammed]], fled to [[Afghanistan]] to avoid Pakistani army operations.<ref name=tguarap/> He was succeeded by Maulana Abu Bakr.<ref name="et20120826">{{cite news|url=http://tribune.com.pk/story/426391/ttp-confirms-death-of-its-bajaur-chief/|title=TTP confirms death of its Bajaur chief|work=The Express Tribune|date=26 August 2012|accessdate=27 August 2012|author=Mohmand, Mureeb}}</ref><ref name=knews>{{cite news|title=TTP confirms Dadullah killing, names new chief of Bajaur|url=http://khybernews.tv/newsDetails.php?cat=13&key=MTgwOTU=|accessdate=25 August 2012|newspaper=Khyber News|date=25 August 2012}}</ref>
